sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects modifications to the "Hidden" and "ShowSuperHidden" explorer registry values in order to disable showing of hidden files and system files.
This technique is abused by several malware families to hide their files from normal users.
Detects modification of autostart extensibility point (ASEP) in registry.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Adversaries may establish persistence by executing malicious content triggered by user inactivity.
Screensavers are programs that execute after a configurable time of user inactivity and consist of Portable Executable (PE) files with a .scr file extension
Detects unusual processes accessing desktop.ini, which can be leveraged to alter how Explorer displays a folder's content (i.e. renaming files) without changing them on disk.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Files With System Process Name In Unsuspected Locations
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects the creation of an executable with a system process name in folders other than the system ones (System32, SysWOW64, etc.).
It is highly recommended to perform an initial baseline before using this rule in production.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Sander Wiebing, Tim Shelton, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Registry Modification to Hidden File Extension
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Hides the file extension through modification of the registry

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Load Of RstrtMgr.DLL By An Uncommon Process
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects the load of RstrtMgr DLL (Restart Manager) by an uncommon process.
This library has been used during ransomware campaigns to kill processes that would prevent file encryption by locking them (e.g. Conti ransomware, Cactus ransomware). It has also recently been seen used by the BiBi wiper for Windows.
It could also be used for anti-analysis purposes by shut downing specific processes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This is a Visual Basic 6.0 binary packed with UPX. It exhibits indicators of legacy worm-like behavior, specifically targeting 'Folder.htt' (PersistMoniker=file://XK\Folder.htt), a technique used by older malware families like VBS.Redlof to achieve persistence and propagation when a user browses infected directories. The binary contains hardcoded strings for file manipulation ('C:\My Documents\My Pictures\4u.txt') and HTML/script injection tags, suggesting it drops or modifies files to execute malicious scripts via ActiveX or Windows Desktop Update vulnerabilities.
